APPENDIX D: HUMAN FACTORS SURVEY INSTRUMENT – PERCEIVED SPATIAL QUALITY (PSQ) SCALE

D.1 Development and Purpose
The Perceived Spatial Quality (PSQ) Scale is a proposed psychometric tool to quantitatively assess the effectiveness of interior design strategies in confined extraterrestrial habitats. It is intended for use in analog missions (e.g., HERA, HI-SEAS) to validate the design principles in Chapter 5.

D.2 The PSQ Scale (Sample Items)
Crew respond on a 7-point Likert scale (1=Strongly Disagree, 7=Strongly Agree) to statements administered weekly.

· Subscale 1: Environmental Control & Autonomy
  · "I can easily adjust the light, temperature, or sound in my personal quarters to my liking."
  · "The common areas of the habitat feel oppressive or inflexible." (Reverse-scored)
· Subscale 2: Spatial Legibility & Orientation
  · "I can easily find my way to any part of the habitat without getting disoriented."
  · "Different areas of the habitat have their own distinct and pleasant character."
· Subscale 3: Sensory Quality & Biophilic Connection
  · "The visual environment is interesting and varied."
  · "I feel a positive connection to natural elements (plants, images of nature, natural materials) within the habitat."
  · "The acoustic environment is generally comfortable, without being overly dead or noisy."
· Subscale 4: Social- Spatial Functionality
  · "The habitat provides adequate spaces for both private time and group socializing."
  · "The design of workspaces supports my productivity and focus."

D.3 Application for Dissertation Validation
Correlations between PSQ scores and objective measures (crew health markers, task performance, interpersonal conflict logs) can be used to empirically validate the human-centered design principles proposed. A declining PSQ score serves as an early warning indicator for required environmental intervention or reconfiguration.

---

APPENDIX E: SIMULATION FRAMEWORK PARAMETERS FOR COLONY DIGITAL TWIN

E.1 Overview
A proposed agent-based and systems-dynamics simulation framework to model the Starship settlement, enabling testing of the modular architecture against stochastic failure events and resource flow disruptions.

E.2 Core Agent Classes

1. Crew Agents: Attributes: Specialization, skill levels, fatigue, social ties. Behavior: Follow daily schedules, perform repairs, respond to emergencies.
2. Module Agents (Starships): Attributes: Functional type, system health states (0-100%), resource stocks (power, O₂, H₂O, food). Behavior: Produce/consume resources, fail probabilistically.
3. Infrastructure Agents: UDS connections, power grid nodes, rovers.

E.3 Key Stochastic Variables & Failure Modes

· System Failures: Modeled via Weibull distributions based on ISS MTBF data (e.g., CO₂ scrubber failure, pump seizure, electrical short).
· Environmental Events: Stochastic dust storms (reducing solar power by 50-95% for 5-50 sols), external radiator micrometeoroid puncture.
· Human Events: Medical emergencies (probabilistic), acute psychological crisis (correlated with PSQ scores).

E.4 Output Metrics for Analysis
The simulation runs for a simulated 5-Earth-year period, tracking:

· Survival Rate: Maintain 100%.
· SSR Progression: Should follow predicted curve.
· MLR Oscillation: Spikes indicate cascading failures.
· Resource Buffer Minimums: Identify critical, under-buffered resources.
· Crew Time Allocation: Validate workforce model.

E.5 Use Case Example
Scenario: A major dust storm coincides with a primary electrolyzer failure in the Industrial Starship.
Simulation Output: Tracks if the settlement's buffered O₂ reserves and power from Energy Starships (via HVDC grid) are sufficient to maintain life support until repairs (requiring specific crew skills and spare parts) can be effected. It quantifies the risk of such a double-contingency and validates (or invalidates) the sizing of buffers and redundancy in the proposed architecture.